fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Monoids in a monoidal category C and monoid homomorphisms form a category, denoted by \text {Mon}(C). When the left-adjoint (-)^* to the forgetful functor U : \text {Mon(C)} \to C exists, it maps an object X to the free monoid on X.

When constructing a semantic model of a system or when structuring computer code, there are several notions of computation that one might consider. The popular ones can be monads, applicative functors and arrows. Each of these notions of computation has particular characteristics that makes them more suitable for some tasks than for others. In fact, these representations can be unified as monoids in a monodial category, and there is much to be gained from unifying all three different notions under a single conceptual framework.
Monads are known to be monoids in a monoidal category of endofunctors
Arrows have been recently shown to be strong monoids in a monoidal category of profunctors
Applicative functors are usually presented as lax monoidal functors with a compatible strength, or monoids in a monoidal category of endofunctors using the Day convolution as a tensor
For every set M we can construct the monoid of endomorphisms (M\to M, \circ , \text {id}).

M is a sub-monoid of a monoid M' if there is an injection i : M \hookrightarrow M' such that i(e) = e' and i(a \circ b) = i(a) \circ ' i(b) for all a, b \in M. Every monoid M is a sub-monoid of the monoid of endomorphisms (M\to M, \circ , \text {id}).

This can be proved by constructing an injection map \text {rep} : M\to (M\to M) by \text {rep} : a \mapsto \lambda x.a\circ x, which is easy to verify that \text {rep} is a monoid homomorphism. Moreover, \text {rep} is an injection, since we have a function \text {abs} : (M\to M) \to M given by \text {abs} : f \mapsto f(e). and \text {abs}\circ \text {rep} = \text {id}_M.
The Cayley representation can be adapted to the List ([a], ++, []) in Haskell, resulting the famous Difference Lists.

fr:pre.html:code:
type EList a = [a] -> [a]
rep :: [a] -> EList a rep xs = (xs ++)
abs :: EList a -> [a] abs f = f []

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
The ordinary notion of monoid in category Set of sets and functions is restrictive, so generalize monoids to other categories. What we need are notions of
a pairing operation for expressing the type of the multiplication,
a type for expressing the unit. We can not directly extend set binary functions X \times X \to X to monoid multiplication in a category, because the category may not have products. Instead, we need to use a bifunctor \otimes : C \times C \to C which abstracts the product operation. The unit object is a special object I in the category.
The idea of currying a function can be generalized to a monoidal category with exponential.

Let A be an object of a monoidal category (C, \otimes , \alpha , \lambda , \rho ). An exponential -^A is the right adjoint to the functor - \otimes A, which is characterised by the an isomorphism: \lfloor -\rfloor : \hom (X \otimes A, B) \cong \hom (X, B^A) : \lceil - \rceil natural in X and B. The counit of the adjunction is the evaluation map \ev _B : B^A \otimes A \to B. When the exponential to A exists, we say A is an exponent. A monoidal category with all exponentials is called a right-closed monoidal category or said to have exponentials.
For a set A we can generate the free monoid A^*. We can then define the notion of free monoid in terms of monoidal category.

Monoids in a monoidal category C and monoid homomorphisms form a category, denoted by \text {Mon}(C). When the left-adjoint (-)^* to the forgetful functor U : \text {Mon(C)} \to C exists, it maps an object X to the free monoid on X.

It is well known that the free monoid over a set A is the set of lists of A. In Haskell this is just the list type List a.
data List a = Nil | Cons a (List a)
Given a monoid (M, e, m) in C, and a monic i : M' \hookrightarrow M in #PC such that for some unique maps e' and m', the following diagram commutes:

fr:resource.fr:resource-source: \begin {tikzcd} && { M} && {M\otimes M} \\ I \\ && {M'} && {M' \otimes M'} \arrow ["m"', from=1-5, to=1-3] \arrow ["e", from=2-1, to=1-3] \arrow ["{e'}", from=2-1, to=3-3] \arrow ["i", from=3-3, to=1-3] \arrow ["{i \otimes i}"', from=3-5, to=1-5] \arrow ["{m'}"', from=3-5, to=3-3] \end {tikzcd}

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Then (M', e', m') is a sub-monoid of (M, e, m), induced by the monic i, which is a monoid monomorphism from M' to M.
Every exponent in a monoidal category induces a monoid of endomorphisms.

Let (C, \otimes , I, \alpha , \lambda , \rho ) be a monoidal category. The monoid of endomorphisms on any exponent A \in C is given by the diagram: I \xrightarrow {i_A} A^A \xleftarrow {c_A} A^A \otimes A^A where i_A and c_A are defined: \begin {align*} i_A &= \lfloor I \otimes A \xrightarrow {\lambda _A} A \rfloor \\ c_A &= \lfloor (A^A \otimes A^A)\otimes A \xrightarrow {\alpha ^{-1}} A^A\otimes (A^A \otimes A) \xrightarrow {\text {id}_{A^A} \otimes \text {ev}_A} A^A\otimes A \xrightarrow {\text {ev}_A} A \rfloor \end {align*}
The Cayley theorem states that every monoid in a monoidal category is a sub-monoid of endomorphisms whenever M is an exponent.

Let \text {End} = ([\text {Set}, \text {Set}], \circ , \text {Id}, \alpha , \lambda , \rho ) be a (strict, i.e. \alpha ,\lambda ,\rho are identities) monoidal category of endofunctors. A monoid in this category consists of
an endofunctor M : \text {Set} \to \text {Set}
a natural transformation \mu : M \circ M \to M
a unit e : \text {Id} \to M such that the following diagrams commute:

fr:resource.fr:resource-source: \begin {tikzcd} {(M \circ M)\circ M} &&&& {M\circ M} \\ \\ {M\circ (M\circ M)} && {M\circ M} && M \arrow ["mM"', from=1-1, to=1-5] \arrow [equal, from=1-1, to=3-1] \arrow ["m", from=1-5, to=3-5] \arrow ["Mm"', from=3-1, to=3-3] \arrow ["m"', from=3-3, to=3-5] \end {tikzcd}

\begin {tikzcd} {M\circ M} && {M\circ \text {Id}} \\ \\ {\text {Id}\circ M} && M \arrow ["m", from=1-1, to=3-3] \arrow ["Me", from=1-3, to=1-1] \arrow [equal, from=1-3, to=3-3] \arrow ["eM", from=3-1, to=1-1] \arrow [equal, from=3-1, to=3-3] \end {tikzcd}

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: A monoid in \text {End} is called a monad. That is where the slogan "a monad is a monoid in the category of endofunctors" comes from.
The monad can be implemented as the type class Triple in Haskell.

fr:pre.html:code: class Functor m => Triple m where unit :: a -> m a join :: m (m a) -> m a

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: The familar implementation is the Kleisli extension one: (Note that one can be obtained from the other by taking unit = return and join = (>>= id), (>>= f) = join . fmap f)

fr:pre.html:code: class Monad m where return :: a -> m a (>>=) :: m a -> (a -> m b) -> m b
